An Act promoting small business growth in the Commonwealth.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 SECTION 1. For the purposes of this act, “Small business” shall mean a business entity,
2 including its affiliates, that (a) is independently owned and operated; (b) has a principal place of
3 business in the commonwealth; and (c) would be defined as a ''small business'' under applicable
4 federal law, as established in the United States Code and promulgated from time to time by the
5 United States Small Business Administration.
6 SECTION 2. Chapter 30A of the General Laws, as appearing in the 2022 Official
7 Edition, is hereby amended by adding the following section:
8 Section 26. Small Business Administrative Rights.
9 (a) All state agencies shall respond to inquiries, requests for information, or other
10 correspondence from small businesses within 24 hours of receipt, excluding weekends and state
11 holidays.
1 of 7

12 (b) State agencies shall notify small businesses by email of any pending rule changes,
13 compliance requirements, or other regulatory updates no later than 7 days after such changes are
14 published.
15 (c) Small businesses shall have the right to a hearing within 30 days of a request to
16 contest violations, penalties, or other adverse actions. Agencies shall provide clear written
17 explanations of any alleged violations, including citations to applicable laws or regulations.
18 (d) State agencies shall provide accessible and plain-language instructions to assist small
19 businesses, in achieving compliance with state regulations. No penalties shall be issued for
20 noncompliance unless the small business is given a reasonable time to rectify the issue, as
21 determined by the agency's rules.
22 SECTION 3. Chapter 62C of the General Laws, as appearing in the 2022 official edition,
23 is hereby amended by adding the following section:
24 Section 19A. One-Year Waiting Period for New Taxes on Small Businesses.
25 (a) Any new tax, fee, or financial charge on small businesses shall not take effect until
26 one year after it is enacted.
27 (b) The Department of Revenue must notify all affected small businesses in writing at
28 least six months before the new tax or fee takes effect. The notice must include: (1) The law or
29 regulation creating the tax or fee; (2) A plain-language summary of its purpose and requirements;
30 And (3) Instructions for how to appeal.
2 of 7

31 (c) Small businesses may appeal the new tax or fee within 30 days of receiving the
32 notice. The Department of Revenue must hold a hearing within 60 days and provide a written
33 decision within 30 days after the hearing.
34 (d) This waiting period may be waived only during a declared state of emergency if the
35 Governor and two-thirds of both legislative chambers approve.
36 SECTION 4. Chapter 93 of the General law, as appearing in the 2022 official edition, is
37 hereby amended by adding the following section:-
38 Section 115. Centralized Permitting and Licensing Portal for Small Businesses.
39 (a) The Secretary of the Commonwealth, in coordination with the Executive Office of
40 Health and Human Services, Executive Office of Economic Development, the Executive Office
41 of Energy and Environmental Affairs, and other relevant state agencies, shall establish and
42 maintain a centralized online portal to streamline licensing, permitting, and registration processes
43 for small businesses, within the Commonwealth.
44 (b) The portal shall: (1) Provide a unified platform for applying, renewing, and tracking
45 compliance for licenses and permits; (2) Include licensing and permitting requirements from all
46 relevant state agencies, boards, and commissions; (3) Offer comprehensive guidance and
47 resources to help small businesses meet compliance requirements; (4) Facilitate secure online
48 payments for applicable fees;(5) include the capability for real-time tracking of permit and
49 license applications, allowing users to monitor the status, progress, and any outstanding
50 requirements in real time; and (6) Include a feedback mechanism for users to report issues or
51 suggest improvements.
3 of 7

52 (c) Each agency, board, and commission overseeing licensing or permitting processes for
53 small businesses shall collaborate with the Secretary of the Commonwealth to integrate their
54 processes into the portal within 12 months of the effective date of this section.
55 (d) The Secretary of the Commonwealth shall adopt regulations to implement this
56 section, including timelines for agency integration and performance benchmarks for the portal.
57 (e) The Secretary shall submit an annual report to the Governor, the Speaker of the
58 House, the Senate President, the Minority Leaders of both chambers, and the Chairs of the Joint
59 Committee on Community Development and Small Businesses. This report shall detail the
60 portal's operations, usage statistics, and provide any recommendations for improvement.
